 Q14. How do outliers affect measures of central tendency and dispersion? Provide an example. 
Outliers can significantly impact measures of central tendency and dispersion in a dataset. An outlier is an extreme value that is much larger or smaller than the majority of the data points in the dataset. The presence of outliers can distort the typical characteristics of the data and affect the calculations of central tendency (mean, median, mode) and measures of dispersion (variance, standard deviation, range).
Consider the following dataset representing the ages of students in a class: [12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 45]

•	Mean: The mean is sensitive to outliers. In this example, adding the outlier (45) significantly affects the mean: Mean without outlier: (12 + 13 + 14 + 15 + 16 + 17 + 18 + 19 + 20) / 9 = 16 Mean with outlier: (12 + 13 + 14 + 15 + 16 + 17 + 18 + 19 + 20 + 45) / 10 = 18
•	Median: The median is less affected by outliers. In this example, the median remains the same even with the outlier: Median: 16 (the middle value of the sorted dataset)
•	Mode: The mode is not impacted by outliers since it represents the most frequently occurring value. In this example, the mode remains the same: Mode: No mode (all values appear only once)
Dispersion:
•	Variance and Standard Deviation: Both variance and standard deviation are influenced by outliers. The squared differences between each data point and the mean are larger when there are extreme values like the outlier, increasing the variance and standard deviation.
•	Range: The range is influenced by outliers as it is simply the difference between the maximum and minimum values. In this example, the range is much larger due to the presence of the outlier: Range without outlier: 20 - 12 = 8 Range with outlier: 45 - 12 = 33
